{"title_page": "Obfusc (musician)", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Obfusc\n| image =\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name = Joseph X. Burke\n| alias = \n| birth_date = {{Birth based on age as of date|32|2014|02|11}}\n| death_date = \n| origin = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| instrument = \n| genre = [[Electronic music|Electronic]], [[Intelligent dance music|IDM]], [[Ambient Music|ambient]], [[downtempo]]\n| years_active = 2005\u2013present\n| label = [[Boltfish Recordings]]<br />[[Static Caravan Recordings]]<br />Expanding Electronic Diversity<br />INSTALL Sound\n| associated_acts = \n| website = [http://www.obfusc.net/ Obfusc.net]\n}}\n\n'''Obfusc''' is the name given to the musical output of '''Joseph X. Burke''' (born 1981), Chicago-based graphic designer and [http://www.josephx.com photographer].<ref>http://www.josephx.com</ref><ref>http://www.obfusc.net</ref> Originally formed in [[Brooklyn]] in 2005 as an [[electronic music]] project, Obfusc has since evolved to include a greater array of live instrumentation and [[post-rock]] influence. Burke is most notably associated with London-based [[Boltfish Recordings]],<ref>http://www.boltfish.co.uk/artists/obfusc.php</ref> but has also released music through [[Static Caravan Recordings]], [http://www.discogs.com/label/50016-Expanding-Electronic-Diversity Expanding Electronic Diversity], [http://www.installsound.net INSTALL Sound], and several other DIY labels.<ref>http://www.discogs.com/artist/416337-Obfusc</ref> His music has been licensed for placement in the Netflix series \"[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]\",<ref>http://www.tunefind.com/show/house-of-cards/season-3/20804</ref> CBS Television's \"[[CSI: Miami]]\",<ref>http://www.tunefind.com/show/csi-miami/season-7/3660</ref> the media campaign for Ustwo Games' \"[[Monument Valley (video game)|Monument Valley]]\",<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vUABzeh55hQ</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wC1jHHF_Wjo</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2P-YKsHpNs</ref> and various web series, short films, and promotional videos.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''Internal Countryside'', 2006 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLT031_internal-countryside.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD-R, Digital\n* ''Cities of Cedar'', 2008 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLTLP003_cities-of-cedar.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD, Digital\n* ''Midnight Dome'', 2011 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLTLP014_midnight-dome.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD, Digital\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Infinite Glimpse'', 2016 (on [https://obfusc.bandcamp.com/album/infinite-glimpse-ep Obfusc Music]) - Digital\n* ''Wrought From The Walls'', 2005 (Self-Released) - CD-R, Digital\n\n===Singles===\n* ''Inverted Island (Day Mix) b/w Oceanic Glow (Night Mix)'', 2009 (on [http://www.staticcaravan.org/item.asp?Ref=194 Static Caravan Recordings]) - 7\" Vinyl\n\n===Split Releases===\n* ''Break It Into Pieces'' (with [http://cheju.bandcamp.com Cheju]), 2005 (on [http://www.discogs.com/CHEjU--Obfusc-Break-It-Into-Pieces/release/626453 Wyrd Skies Recordings]) - CD-R, Digital\n* ''Untitled'' (with [http://davidtagg.net David Tagg]), 2009 (on [http://www.installsound.net/catalog.htm#s4 INSTALL Sound]) - 2 x 3\" CD-R, Digital\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* ''Monument Valley (Original Soundtrack: Volumes I & II)'' (with Stafford Bawler & Grigori), 2016 (on [http://store.iam8bit.com/collections/monument-valley/products/monument-valley-vinyl-soundtrack-2xlp iam8bit]) - 2 x 12\" Vinyl\n* ''Monument Valley (Original Soundtrack)'' (with Stafford Bawler & Grigori), 2014 (on [https://twitter.com/ustwogames/status/492339672321101824 Ustwo Games]) - Digital\n\n===Music Videos===\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k4zStnjR48M Before We Lose Our Legs]'', 2006 (Directed by [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1557549/ Jason Banker])\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SryXlZL7ebc Amateur Cartography]'', 2008 (Directed by [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1557549/ Jason Banker], featuring [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5077742/?ref_=tt_ov_st James Davidson])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.obfusc.net Official website]\n* [https://twitter.com/josephxburke Official Twitter]\n* [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/artists/obfusc.php Boltfish Recordings Artist Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obfusc}}\n[[Category:Ambient music]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Obfusc\n| image =\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name = Joseph X. Burke\n| alias = \n| birth_date = {{Birth based on age as of date|32|2014|02|11}}\n| death_date = \n| origin = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| instrument = \n| genre = [[Electronic music|Electronic]], [[Intelligent dance music|IDM]], [[Ambient Music|ambient]], [[downtempo]]\n| years_active = 2005\u2013present\n| label = [[Boltfish Recordings]]<br>[[Static Caravan Recordings]]<br>Expanding Electronic Diversity<br>INSTALL Sound\n| associated_acts = \n| website = [http://www.obfusc.net/ Obfusc.net]\n}}\n\n'''Obfusc''' is the name given to the musical output of '''Joseph X. Burke''' (born 1981), Chicago-based graphic designer and [http://www.josephx.com photographer].<ref>http://www.josephx.com</ref><ref>http://www.obfusc.net</ref> Originally formed in [[Brooklyn]] in 2005 as an [[electronic music]] project, Obfusc has since evolved to include a greater array of live instrumentation and [[post-rock]] influence. Burke is most notably associated with London-based [[Boltfish Recordings]],<ref>http://www.boltfish.co.uk/artists/obfusc.php</ref> but has also released music through [[Static Caravan Recordings]], [http://www.discogs.com/label/50016-Expanding-Electronic-Diversity Expanding Electronic Diversity], [http://www.installsound.net INSTALL Sound], and several other DIY labels.<ref>http://www.discogs.com/artist/416337-Obfusc</ref> His music has been licensed for placement in the Netflix series \"[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]\",<ref>http://www.tunefind.com/show/house-of-cards/season-3/20804</ref> CBS Television's \"[[CSI: Miami]]\",<ref>http://www.tunefind.com/show/csi-miami/season-7/3660</ref> the media campaign for Ustwo Games' \"[[Monument Valley (video game)|Monument Valley]]\",<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vUABzeh55hQ</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wC1jHHF_Wjo</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2P-YKsHpNs</ref> and various web series, short films, and promotional videos.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''Internal Countryside'', 2006 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLT031_internal-countryside.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD-R, Digital\n* ''Cities of Cedar'', 2008 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLTLP003_cities-of-cedar.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD, Digital\n* ''Midnight Dome'', 2011 (on [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/releases/BOLTLP014_midnight-dome.php Boltfish Recordings]) - CD, Digital\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Infinite Glimpse'', 2016 (on [https://obfusc.bandcamp.com/album/infinite-glimpse-ep Obfusc Music]) - Digital\n* ''Wrought From The Walls'', 2005 (Self-Released) - CD-R, Digital\n\n===Singles===\n* ''Inverted Island (Day Mix) b/w Oceanic Glow (Night Mix)'', 2009 (on [http://www.staticcaravan.org/item.asp?Ref=194 Static Caravan Recordings]) - 7\" Vinyl\n\n===Split Releases===\n* ''Break It Into Pieces'' (with [http://cheju.bandcamp.com Cheju]), 2005 (on [http://www.discogs.com/CHEjU--Obfusc-Break-It-Into-Pieces/release/626453 Wyrd Skies Recordings]) - CD-R, Digital\n* ''Untitled'' (with [http://davidtagg.net David Tagg]), 2009 (on [http://www.installsound.net/catalog.htm#s4 INSTALL Sound]) - 2 x 3\" CD-R, Digital\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* ''Monument Valley (Original Soundtrack: Volumes I & II)'' (with Stafford Bawler & Grigori), 2016 (on [http://store.iam8bit.com/collections/monument-valley/products/monument-valley-vinyl-soundtrack-2xlp iam8bit]) - 2 x 12\" Vinyl\n* ''Monument Valley (Original Soundtrack)'' (with Stafford Bawler & Grigori), 2014 (on [https://twitter.com/ustwogames/status/492339672321101824 Ustwo Games]) - Digital\n\n===Music Videos===\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k4zStnjR48M Before We Lose Our Legs]'', 2006 (Directed by [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1557549/ Jason Banker])\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SryXlZL7ebc Amateur Cartography]'', 2008 (Directed by [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1557549/ Jason Banker], featuring [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5077742/?ref_=tt_ov_st James Davidson])\n\n==References==\n:{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.obfusc.net Official website]\n* [https://twitter.com/josephxburke Official Twitter]\n* [http://www.boltfish.co.uk/artists/obfusc.php Boltfish Recordings Artist Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obfusc}}\n[[Category:Ambient music]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obfusc_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Cairo International Stadium", "text_new": "{{Infobox stadium\n| name                = Cairo International Stadium\n| nickname            = \u0633\u062a\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0649\n| logo_image          =  \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = [[File:Panorma Cairo Stadium.jpg|250px]]\n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Cairo International Stadium\n| former_names        = Nasser Stadium\n| location            = [[Nasr City]], [[Cairo]]\n| coordinates         = \n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = 1955\u20131960\n| opened              = 23 July 1960\n| renovated           = 2005, 2019\n| expanded            = \n| closed              = \n| demolished          = \n| owner               = \n| operator            = \n| surface             = [[Desso GrassMaster]]\n| scoreboard          = \n| cost                = \n| architect           = [[Werner March]]\n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer =[[ACE Moharram Bakhoum]] \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 74,000\n| suites              = \n| record_attendance   = 120,000\n| dimensions          = \n| acreage             = \n| tenants             = [[Egypt national football team]]<br />[[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]]<br />[[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n}}\nThe '''Cairo International Stadium''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u062a\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0649}}), formerly known as '''Nasser Stadium''', is an Olympic-standard, multi-use [[stadium]] with an all-seated capacity of 75,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cairo-stadium.org.eg/articlesdetail.aspx?id=N10|title=International Cairo Stadium|website=www.cairo-stadium.org.eg|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> The architect of the stadium is the German [[Werner March]], who had built from 1934 to 1936 the [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympic Stadium]] in Berlin. The engineering and construction supervision work of the stadium was performed by [[ACE Moharram Bakhoum]]. Before becoming an all seater stadium, it had the ability to hold over 100,000 spectators, reaching a record of 120,000. It is the foremost Olympic-standard facility befitting the role of [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] as the center of events in the region. It is also the 69th largest stadium in the world. Located in [[Nasr City]]; a suburb north east of [[Cairo]], it was completed in 1960, and was inaugurated by [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|President Gamal Abd El Nasser]] on 23 July that year, the eighth anniversary of the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952]]. [[Zamalek SC]] and [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] use [[Cairo International Stadium]] for most of their home games.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Stadium is located about 10&nbsp;km west of [[Cairo International Airport]] and about 10&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g.co/maps/qa5bd |title=Distance &amp; Directions from Cairo Stadium to Downtown |publisher=Google |accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> (30 min) from downtown Cairo.\n\nIn 2005, in preparation for the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]] it underwent a major renovation, and was brought up to 21st century world standard along with all its multi-game Olympic facilities.\n\nCairo Stadium is known for its tremendous atmosphere and its very large capacity. This was never more evident than during the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]], which were held in Egypt. When Egypt had their matches in Cairo Stadium, the stadium seemed to nearly erupt.\nBefore seats were added to all sections in 2005, the stadium was notorious for holding more people than it was intended to. Without seats, fans were able to squeeze together and sit in aisles. Because of the previous seating layout, Cairo International Stadium was able to host over 120,000 fans for the 1986 African Cup of Nations Final match between Egypt and Cameroon. Behind the enormous crowd, hosts Egypt defeated Cameroon.\n\nCairo Stadium is a strong symbol of Egyptian football. Nearly all of the most important Egyptian matches are held there. It carries an extremely rich history which includes many memorable football moments that range from Hossam Hassan's famous header to secure Egypt's attendance in Italia 90 World Cup, numerous African Cup of Nations tournaments which included the latest 2006 trophy, and the famous derby matches between Ahly and Zamalek.\n\nIt has also served as the main stadium of the [[1991 All-Africa Games]].\n\n==2019 Africa Cup of Nations==\nThe stadium was one of the venues for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].\n\nThe following games were played at the stadium during the 2019  Africa Cup of Nations:\n\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Time ([[Central European Summer Time|CEST]])\n!Team #1\n!Result\n!Team #2\n!Round\n!Attendance\n|-\n|21 June 2019||22:00||{{fb|EGY}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20130||{{fb|ZIM}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 73,299\n|-\n|22 June 2019||16:30||{{fb|DRC}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20132||{{fb|UGA}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,083\n|-\n|26 June 2019||19:00||{{fb|UGA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||{{fb|ZIM}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 73,589\n|-\n|26 June 2019||22:00||{{fb|EGY}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||{{fb|DRC}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 74,219\n|-\n|30 June 2019||21:00||{{fb|UGA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20132||{{fb|EGY}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|74,566\n|-\n|5 July 2019||21:00||{{fb|UGA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||{{fb|SEN}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations#Round of 16|Round of 16]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|6,950\n|-\n|6 July 2019||21:00||{{fb|EGY}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||{{fb|RSA}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations#Round of 16|Round of 16]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|75,000\n|-\n|10 July 2019||21:00||{{fb|NGA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20131||{{fb|RSA}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations#Quarter_finals|Quarter-finals]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|48,343\n|-\n|14 July 2019||21:00||{{fb|ALG}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20131|||{{fb|NGA}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|Semi-finals]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|49,775\n|-\n|19 July 2019||21:00||{{fb|SEN}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||{{fb|ALG}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Final|Final]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|75,000\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Cairo International Stadium.jpg|A view of the stadium in 2006.\nFile:Crowd in Cairo Stadium.jpg|Egyptian supporters attending a match involving the national team in 2007.\nFile:Cairo International Stadium 2019.jpg|A view of the stadium minutes before the match between Uganda and Zimbabwe during AFCON 2019\nFile:Cairo Stadium Afcon u23 2019.jpg|Cairo stadium during Egypt u23 vs south africa u23 match\nFile: Afcon u23 closing ceremony1.jpg|Cairo stadium during AFCON U23 Closing ceremoney\nFile: Afcon u23 closing ceremony2.jpg|Cairo stadium during AFCON U23 Closing ceremoney\nFile: Afcon u23 closing ceremony3.jpg|Cairo stadium during AFCON U23 Closing ceremoney\n\n</gallery>\n{{wide image|Panorma Cairo Stadium.jpg|800px|align-cap=center|A Panorama view of the stadium interior|100%}}\n\n{{wide image| Al Ahly Vs Sundowns 2020.jpg |800px|align-cap=center| Cairo Stadium before Al Ahly Vs Sundowns match In CAF Chanpions League|100%}}\n\n==Trivia==\n*Hosts matches between Cairo giants [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] and [[Zamalek SC]], some with attendances above 100,000.\n*Hosts matches for the [[Egypt national football team]].\n*In the [[1986 Africa Cup of Nations]] it was packed with 120,000 people to see their team winning the tournament against [[Cameroon]].\n*Hosted many matches in the [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]] and the final which Egypt won against [[Ivory Coast]] 4-2 in [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalties]] shootouts after a 0-0 draw [[Overtime]] which was packed with 80,000 attendance.\n*It is the most visited stadium in Egypt having all of the important matches for the [[Egypt national football team]].\n*It was updated to host the [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]] to meet the [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] standard stadiums making it all-seated which decreased the capacity from 85,000 to 75,000 and making blue zigzag highlights on the seats, later on the Olympic track was changed from blue to orange it was first seen on 14 November when Egypt faced [[Algeria]] in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)]] which Egypt won 2-0.\n*It was one of the stadiums along with [[Borg El Arab Stadium]] and 5 other planned stadiums in the failed Egyptian bid to host the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cairo Stadium Indoor Halls Complex]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Cairo International Stadium}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170409152459/http://www.cairo-stadium.org.eg/ Website for Cairo Stadium]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090215003605/http://worldstadiums.com/stadium_pictures/middle_east/egypt/cairo_stadium.shtml Photos] at [http://www.worldstadiums.com/ worldstadiums.com]\n*[http://www.fussballtempel.net/caf/EGY/Cairo_International.html Photos] at [http://www.fussballtempel.net/ fussballtempel.net]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[African Cup of Nations]]<br>Final Venue\n | years = [[2006 African Cup of Nations|2006]]\n | before = [[Stade 7 November]] <br>[[Rades]]\n | after = [[Ohene Djan Stadium]] <br/> [[Accra]]\n}}\n{{Succession box |\n  title=[[FIFA U-20 World Cup]]<br>Final Venue|\n  before=[[BMO Field|National Soccer Stadium]] <br>[[Toronto]]|\n  after=[[Estadio El Camp\u00edn|Estadio Nemesio Camacho]] <br>[[Bogot\u00e1]]|\n  years=[[2009 FIFA U-20 World Cup|2009]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Football in Egypt}}\n{{Egyptian Premier League}}\n{{2019 Africa Cup of Nations stadiums}}\n{{coord|30|4|8.81|N|31|18|44.40|E|region:EG_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Zamalek SC]]\n[[Category:Football venues in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Stadiums in Cairo]]\n[[Category:National stadiums|Egypt]]\n[[Category:Stadiums of the African Games]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1960]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Football in Cairo]]\n[[Category:2019 Africa Cup of Nations stadiums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox stadium\n| name                = Cairo International Stadium\n| nickname            = \u0633\u062a\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0649\n| logo_image          =  \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = [[File:Panorma Cairo Stadium.jpg|250px]]\n| caption             = \n| fullname            = Cairo International Stadium\n| former_names        = Nasser Stadium\n| location            = [[Nasr City]], [[Cairo]]\n| coordinates         = \n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = 1955\u20131960\n| opened              = 23 July 1960\n| renovated           = 2005, 2019\n| expanded            = \n| closed              = \n| demolished          = \n| owner               = \n| operator            = \n| surface             = [[Desso GrassMaster]]\n| scoreboard          = \n| cost                = \n| architect           = [[Werner March]]\n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 74,000\n| suites              = \n| record_attendance   = 120,000\n| dimensions          = \n| acreage             = \n| tenants             = [[Egypt national football team]]<br />[[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]]<br />[[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]]\n}}\nThe '''Cairo International Stadium''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u062a\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0649}}), formerly known as '''Nasser Stadium''', is an Olympic-standard, multi-use [[stadium]] with an all-seated capacity of 75,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cairo-stadium.org.eg/articlesdetail.aspx?id=N10|title=International Cairo Stadium|website=www.cairo-stadium.org.eg|access-date=2017-02-11}}</ref> The architect of the stadium is the German [[Werner March]], who had built from 1934 to 1936 the [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympic Stadium]] in Berlin. Before becoming an all seater stadium, it had the ability to hold over 100,000 spectators, reaching a record of 120,000. It is the foremost Olympic-standard facility befitting the role of [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] as the center of events in the region. It is also the 69th largest stadium in the world. Located in [[Nasr City]]; a suburb north east of [[Cairo]], it was completed in 1960, and was inaugurated by [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|President Gamal Abd El Nasser]] on 23 July that year, the eighth anniversary of the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952]]. [[Zamalek SC]] and [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] use [[Cairo International Stadium]] for most of their home games.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Stadium is located about 10&nbsp;km west of [[Cairo International Airport]] and about 10&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g.co/maps/qa5bd |title=Distance &amp; Directions from Cairo Stadium to Downtown |publisher=Google |accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> (30 min) from downtown Cairo.\n\nIn 2005, in preparation for the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]] it underwent a major renovation, and was brought up to 21st century world standard along with all its multi-game Olympic facilities.\n\nCairo Stadium is known for its tremendous atmosphere and its very large capacity. This was never more evident than during the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]], which were held in Egypt. When Egypt had their matches in Cairo Stadium, the stadium seemed to nearly erupt.\nBefore seats were added to all sections in 2005, the stadium was notorious for holding more people than it was intended to. Without seats, fans were able to squeeze together and sit in aisles. Because of the previous seating layout, Cairo International Stadium was able to host over 120,000 fans for the 1986 African Cup of Nations Final match between Egypt and Cameroon. Behind the enormous crowd, hosts Egypt defeated Cameroon.\n\nCairo Stadium is a strong symbol of Egyptian football. Nearly all of the most important Egyptian matches are held there. It carries an extremely rich history which includes many memorable football moments that range from Hossam Hassan's famous header to secure Egypt's attendance in Italia 90 World Cup, numerous African Cup of Nations tournaments which included the latest 2006 trophy, and the famous derby matches between Ahly and Zamalek.\n\nIt has also served as the main stadium of the [[1991 All-Africa Games]].\n\n==2019 Africa Cup of Nations==\nThe stadium was one of the venues for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].\n\nThe following games were played at the stadium during the 2019  Africa Cup of Nations:\n\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Time ([[Central European Summer Time|CEST]])\n!Team #1\n!Result\n!Team #2\n!Round\n!Attendance\n|-\n|21 June 2019||22:00||{{fb|EGY}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20130||{{fb|ZIM}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 73,299\n|-\n|22 June 2019||16:30||{{fb|DRC}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20132||{{fb|UGA}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,083\n|-\n|26 June 2019||19:00||{{fb|UGA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||{{fb|ZIM}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 73,589\n|-\n|26 June 2019||22:00||{{fb|EGY}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||{{fb|DRC}}||[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group A|Group A]]||style=\"text-align:center;